		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">Spatially homogenous PDEs are ubiquitous in mathematical physics.  In this project, we concentrate on spatial domains that are strips, half-planes or the Euclidean space Rn, and on equations for which the existence of a so called primary localised solution is known.  We shall investigate under which reasonable conditions multibump localised solutions exist, that is, when solutions which are concatenations of widely spaced copies of the primary solutions exist.  There are classical results for one-dimensional problems due to Shilnikov and Devaney that are deeply connected with chaos theory.  However, their standard proofs rely on geometrical considerations that are not transposable to higher-dimensional domains.  Instead, we shall tackle the question with functional analytical tools that have been recently developed in the Calculus of Variations and successfully applied to various situations (e.g. spatially periodic, autonomous and almost periodic Lagrangian systems).  The main physical problems what will be at the centre of this research stem from water-wave theory and vorticity dynamics.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
